<li id="cite_note-china-14">^ <a href="#cite_ref-china_14-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-china_14-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="news">"<a href="http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/ezine/2007-05/16/content_873529.htm" class="external text" title="http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/ezine/2007-05/16/content_873529.htm" rel="nofollow">Do we need our own Mother's Day?</a>". <i><a href="/wiki/China_Daily" title="China Daily">China Daily</a></i>. 2007-05-16<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/ezine/2007-05/16/content_873529.htm" class="external free" title="http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/ezine/2007-05/16/content_873529.htm" rel="nofollow">http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/ezine/2007-05/16/content_873529.htm</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Do+we+need+our+own+Mother%27s+Day%3F&amp;rft.jtitle=%5B%5BChina+Daily%5D%5D&amp;rft.date=2007-05-16&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.chinadaily.com.cn%2Fezine%2F2007-05%2F16%2Fcontent_873529.htm&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Mother%27s_Day"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-15"><b><a href="#cite_ref-15" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFShahin_Gerami1996">Shahin Gerami (1996). <i><a href="http://www.dhushara.com/book/zulu/islamp/wiff/wif.htm" class="external text" title="http://www.dhushara.com/book/zulu/islamp/wiff/wif.htm" rel="nofollow">Women in Fundamentalism</a></i>. New York: Garland Publishing. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0815306636" class="internal">ISBN 0-8153-0663-6</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.dhushara.com/book/zulu/islamp/wiff/wif.htm" class="external free" title="http://www.dhushara.com/book/zulu/islamp/wiff/wif.htm" rel="nofollow">http://www.dhushara.com/book/zulu/islamp/wiff/wif.htm</a></span>.  "To this end, to counteract the Mother's Day of the previous regime, the state first moved it to December 16 [that was the date for that year?], to coincide with Fatemeh's birthday. Then it was expanded to a week with festivities, celebrations, speeches, gifts, prizes, and honors for achieving women."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Women+in+Fundamentalism&amp;rft.aulast=Shahin+Gerami&amp;rft.au=Shahin+Gerami&amp;rft.date=1996&amp;rft.place=New+York&amp;rft.pub=Garland+Publishing&amp;rft.isbn=0-8153-0663-6&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.dhushara.com%2Fbook%2Fzulu%2Fislamp%2Fwiff%2Fwif.htm&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Mother%27s_Day"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span> <a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=FoF5jCEepGkC&amp;pg=PA197&amp;dq=%22mother%27s+day%22+iran+fatimah&amp;lr=&amp;client=opera&amp;hl=es&amp;sig=ACfU3U3yD--Xrd6MwGwScS_OHNvSf5a2Kg" class="external text" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=FoF5jCEepGkC&amp;pg=PA197&amp;dq=%22mother%27s+day%22+iran+fatimah&amp;lr=&amp;client=opera&amp;hl=es&amp;sig=ACfU3U3yD--Xrd6MwGwScS_OHNvSf5a2Kg" rel="nofollow">online version</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-16"><b><a href="#cite_ref-16" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFAli_Akbar_Mahdi2003">Ali Akbar Mahdi (2003). <a href="http://www.owu.edu/~aamahdi/globalization-final.doc" class="external text" title="http://www.owu.edu/~aamahdi/globalization-final.doc" rel="nofollow">"Iranian Women: Between Islamization and Globalization"</a> (DOC). <i>Iran Encountering Globalisation: Problems and Prospects</i>. Ali Mohammadi. London and New York: Routledge/Curzon. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0415308275" class="internal">ISBN 0415308275</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.owu.edu/~aamahdi/globalization-final.doc" class="external free" title="http://www.owu.edu/~aamahdi/globalization-final.doc" rel="nofollow">http://www.owu.edu/~aamahdi/globalization-final.doc</a></span>.  "Other role models for women often cited by the officials and ideologues of the IRI are Khadijah, the prophet Mohammad's wife, and Zaynab, daughter of the first Shi'i Imam Ali. In fact, the IRI replaced the universal Mother's Day with Fatima Zahar's birthday."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Iranian+Women%3A+Between+Islamization+and+Globalization&amp;rft.atitle=Iran+Encountering+Globalisation%3A+Problems+and+Prospects&amp;rft.aulast=Ali+Akbar+Mahdi&amp;rft.au=Ali+Akbar+Mahdi&amp;rft.date=2003&amp;rft.pub=Ali+Mohammadi.+London+and+New+York%3A+Routledge%2FCurzon&amp;rft.isbn=0415308275&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.owu.edu%2F%7Eaamahdi%2Fglobalization-final.doc&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Mother%27s_Day"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
