<blockquote class="templatequote">
<div>
<p>in 1914 Congress passed a law, which Wilson signed on May 8, 1914, "designating the second Sunday in May as Mother's Day," and authorising and requesting that Wilson issue a proclamation "calling upon the government officials to display the United States flag on all buildings, and the people of the United States to display the flag at their homes or other suitable places on the second Sunday in May as a public expression of our love and reverence for the mothers of our country."</p>
</div>
</blockquote>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-21"><b><a href="#cite_ref-21" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/index.php?pid=14859" class="external text" title="http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/index.php?pid=14859" rel="nofollow">71 - Mother's Day Proclamation</a>, <a href="/wiki/Franklin_D._Roosevelt" title="Franklin D. Roosevelt">Franklin D. Roosevelt</a>, May 3, 1934.</li>
<li id="cite_note-9may-22">^ <a href="#cite_ref-9may_22-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-9may_22-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="http://memory.loc.gov/ammem/today/may09.html" class="external text" title="http://memory.loc.gov/ammem/today/may09.html" rel="nofollow">Today in History: May 9</a> Library of Congress</li>
<li id="cite_note-leigh_274-23">^ <a href="#cite_ref-leigh_274_23-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-leigh_274_23-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> Leigh, 1997, pag <a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=maF8mTPsJqsC&amp;pg=PA274&amp;dq=red+white+carnation+mother%27s+day&amp;lr=&amp;hl=es" class="external text" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=maF8mTPsJqsC&amp;pg=PA274&amp;dq=red+white+carnation+mother%27s+day&amp;lr=&amp;hl=es" rel="nofollow">274</a></li>
